<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911224-0023</DOCNO><DOCID>911224-0023.</DOCID><HL>   Keating Set to Be Released   As $300,000 Bail Is Posted</HL><DATE>12/24/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B6</SO><CO>   X-AMC</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)LAW andamp; LEGAL ISSUES AND LEGISLATION (LAW)</NS><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><RE>ARIZONA (AZ)CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Former Lincoln Savings andamp; Loan ownerCharles Keating Jr. posted bail yesterday and was set to bereleased, but his son remains jailed.   Late yesterday one of Mr. Keating's sons-in-law, ThomasMulhern, posted the final $14,000 of a $300,000 bail amountrequired to free him. But the bail was promised too late forpaperwork to be completed for Mr. Keating's release lastnight. He is set to be released from the MetropolitanDetention Center today.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Keating, 68 years old, and his son, Charles KeatingIII, were both indicted and jailed on federal racketeeringand fraud charges.   At a hearing last week, the elder Mr. Keating's bail wasreduced to $300,000 from $2 million. His son's bail wasreduced to $150,000 from $300,000.   Mr. Mulhern and other family members have posted threeproperties with equity of $286,000 toward the $300,000 bailfor the older Mr. Keating.   The younger Mr. Keating was unable to meet his bail. Noone would come forward to post property &quot;because their nameswould be in the paper tomorrow,&quot; said public defender DennisLandin.   Keating, his son, and three other defendants are chargedin a 77-count indictment that accuses them of using fivecomplex schemes to swindle more than $250 million fromLincoln Savings andamp; Loan and from investors who bought bondsissued by Lincoln parent, American Continental Corp. ofPhoenix, Ariz.</TEXT></DOC>